    <p>I'm 64. When I tried the barcode-scanner apps, the first thing I noticed was how little of what I actually eat has a barcode. Three eggs I scrambled this morning — no barcode. The rotisserie chicken I pulled apart for lunch — no barcode. The ground beef I cooked for dinner — no barcode.</p>

    <p>The scanner was supposed to make tracking easier. Instead it became the thing I had to work around every single meal. That friction compounds. And friction is what kills the habit.</p>

